obj_root_law_sections_42_content:
  string
  line 42
  line `( 3 ) The status of the executor or executors shall for the purposes of this Act as regards residence and`
  line `citizenship be the same as that of the deceased on the valuation date immediately preceding his death.`
  line `( 4 ) The assessment of an executor under this section shall be made separately from any assessment`
  line `that may be made on him in respect of his own net wealth or on the net wealth of the deceased under`
  line `section 19.`
  line `( 5 ) Separate assessments shall be made under this section in respect of the net wealth as on each`
  line `valuation date as is included in the period from the date of the death of the deceased to the date of`
  line `complete distribution to the beneficiaries of the estate according to their several interests.`
  line `( 6 ) In computing the net wealth on any valuation date under this section, any assets of the estate`
  line `distributed to, or applied to the benefit of, any specific legatee of the estate prior to that valuation date`
  line `shall be excluded, but the assets so excluded shall, to the extent such assets are held by the legatee on any`
  line `valuation date, be included in the net wealth of such specific legatee on that valuation date.`
  line `Explanation. — In this section, “ executor ” includes an administrator or other person administering the`
  line `estate of a deceased person.]`
  line `20. Assessment after partition of a Hindu undivided family. — ( 1 ) Where, at the time of making an`
  line `assessment, it is brought to the notice of the 1 [Assessing Officer] that a partition has taken place among`
  line `the members of a Hindu undivided family, and the 1 [Assessing Officer], after inquiry, is satisfied that the`
  line `joint family property has been partitioned as a whole among the various members or group of members in`
  line `definite portions, he shall record an order to that effect and shall make assessment on the net wealth of the`
  line `undivided family as such for the assessment year or years, including the year relevant to the previous year`
  line `in which the partition has taken place, if the partition has taken place on the last day of the previous year`
  line `and each member or group of members shall be liable jointly and severally for the tax assessed on the net`
  line `wealth of the joint family as such.`
  line `( 2 ) Where the 1 [Assessing Officer] is not so satisfied, he may, by order, declare that such family shall`
  line `be deemed for the purposes of this Act to continue to be a Hindu undivided family liable to be assessed as`
  line such.
  line `2 [ 20A. Assessment after partial partition of a Hindu undivided family. — Where a partial partition`
  line `has taken place after the 31st day of December, 1978, among the members of a Hindu undivided family`
  line `hitherto assessed as undivided, —`
  line `( a ) such family shall continue to be liable to be assessed under this Act as if no such partial`
  line `partition had taken place;`
  line `( b ) each member or group of members of such family immediately before such partial partition`
  line `and the family shall be jointly and severally liable for any tax, penalty, interest, fine or other sum`
  line `payable under this Act by the family in respect of any period, whether before or after such partial`
  line partition;
  line `( c ) the several liability of any member or group of members aforesaid shall be computed`
  line `according to the portion of the joint family property allotted to him or it at such partial partition,`
  line `and the provisions of this Act shall apply accordingly.`
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this section, “ partial partition ” shall have the meaning assigned to`
  line `it in clause ( b ) of the Explanation to section 171 of the Income-tax Act.]`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 4 of 1988, s. 127, for “Wealth - tax Officer” (w. e.f. 1-4-1988).`
  line `2. Ins. by Act 44 of 1980, s. 39 (w.e.f. 1-4-1980).`
