obj_root_law_sections_69_content:
  string
  line 69
  line `1 [( 3B ) The High Court may admit an application after the expiry of the period of ninety days referred`
  line `to in sub-section ( 3 ), if it is satisfied that there was sufficient cause for not filing the same within that`
  line period.]
  line `( 4 ) The statement to the High Court 2 [or the Supreme Court] shall set forth the facts, the`
  line `determination of the Appellate Tribunal and the question of law which arises out of the case.`
  line `( 5 ) If the High Court 2 [or the Supreme Court], is not satisfied that the case as stated is sufficient to`
  line `enable it to determine the question of law raised thereby, it may require the Appellate Tribunal to make`
  line `such modifications therein as it may direct.`
  line `( 6 ) The High Court 2 [or the Supreme Court], upon hearing any such case, shall decide the question of`
  line `law raised therein, and in doing so, may, if it thinks fit, alter the form of the question of law and shall`
  line `deliver judgment thereon containing the ground on which such decision is founded and shall send a copy`
  line `of the judgment under the seal of the Court and the signature of the Registrar to the Appellate Tribunal`
  line `and the Appellate Tribunal shall pass such orders as are necessary to dispose of the case conformably to`
  line `such judgment.`
  line `3 [( 7 ) The cost of any reference to the High Court or the Supreme Court which shall not include the fee`
  line `for making the reference, shall be in the discretion of the Court.]`
  line `4 [27A. Appeal to High Court. — ( 1 ) The assessee or the Chief Commissioner or Commissioner may,`
  line `within one hundred and twenty days of the day upon which he is served with notice of an order under`
  line `section 24 or section 26 or clause ( e ) of sub-section ( 1 ) of section 35, file on or after the 1st day of`
  line `October, 1998, 5 [but before the date of establishment of the National Tax Tribunal] an appeal before the`
  line `High Court.`
  line `6 [( 1A ) The High Court may admit an appeal after the expiry of the period of one hundred and twenty`
  line `days referred to in sub-section ( 1 ), if it is satisfied that there was sufficient cause for not filing the same`
  line `within that period.]`
  line `( 2 ) An appeal shall lie to the High Court 5 [before the date of establishment of the National Tax`
  line `Tribunal] from every order passed in appeal by the Appellate Tribunal, under sub-section ( 1 ) of`
  line `section 24 only if the High Court is satisfied that the case involves a substantial question of law.`
  line `( 3 ) In an appeal under this section, the Memorandum of Appeal shall precisely state the substantial`
  line `question of law involved in the appeal 7 ***.`
  line `( 4 ) Where the High Court is satisfied that a substantial question of law is involved in any case, it shall`
  line `formulate that question.`
  line `( 5 ) The appeal shall be heard only on the question so formulated and the respondent shall, at the time`
  line `of hearing of the appeal, be allowed to argue that the case does not involve such question:`
  line `Provided that nothing in this sub-section shall be deemed to take away or abridge the power of the`
  line `Court to hear, for reasons to be recorded, the appeal on any other substantial question of law not`
  line `formulated by it, if it is satisfied that the case involves such question.`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 14 of 2010, s. 55 (w.r.e.f. 1-6-1981).`
  line `2. Ins. by Act 46 of 1964, s. 26 (w.e.f. 1-4-1965).`
  line `3. Subs. by s. 26, ibid., for sub-sections ( 7 ), ( 8 ) and ( 9 ) (w.e.f. 1-4-1965).`
  line `4. Ins. by Act 21 of 1998, s. 72 (w.e.f. 1-10-1998).`
  line `5. Ins. by Act 49 of 2005, s. 30 and the Schedule. This Act has been struck down by the Supreme Court’s Order dated 25th`
  line `September, 2014 in the Madras Bar Association Vs. Union of India.`
  line `6. Ins. by Act 14 of 2010, s. 56 (w.r.e.f. 1-10-1998).`
  line `7. The words “, and, where the appeal is made by the assessee, shall be accompanied by a fee of five thousand rupees” omitted by`
  line `Act 27 of 1999, s. 96 (w.e.f. 1-6-1999).`
obj_root_law_sections_69_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_70:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-70
  sectionNo (70)
